472
00:27:43,680 --> 00:27:45,520
It looks very small, far away.

473
00:27:45,520 --> 00:27:47,360
I might be driving toward Dallas.

474
00:27:47,360 --> 00:27:50,360
I see the Dallas skyline, but I'm far away.

475
00:27:50,360 --> 00:27:53,000
And I think, well, Dallas doesn't look that impressive.

476
00:27:53,000 --> 00:27:57,440
But then when I get up close to it, I realize, oh, this is a big city, and it looks much

477
00:27:57,440 --> 00:27:58,920
more impressive.

478
00:27:58,920 --> 00:28:02,360
The same thing can happen when you're flying over something.

479
00:28:02,360 --> 00:28:06,200
Imagine being in an airplane looking down on, let's say, New York City.

480
00:28:06,200 --> 00:28:08,300
I've often flown over New York City.

481
00:28:08,300 --> 00:28:13,960
You look down, and from a distance or a very high height, it doesn't look that big.

482
00:28:13,960 --> 00:28:16,400
And the buildings there are barely discernible.

483
00:28:16,400 --> 00:28:17,640
It looks tiny.

484
00:28:17,640 --> 00:28:22,240
But on the other hand, when you're flying much lower over it, things look large.

485
00:28:22,240 --> 00:28:26,440
And of course, if you're there just in a building, like at the top of the Empire State Building

486
00:28:26,440 --> 00:28:29,280
looking at it, it looks huge.

487
00:28:29,280 --> 00:28:32,760
So New York City is something that looks gigantic.

488
00:28:32,760 --> 00:28:36,000
When you're close up, it can look small if you're far away.

489
00:28:36,000 --> 00:28:40,220
You might have had the experience being very in a very tall tower, a tall office building

490
00:28:40,220 --> 00:28:44,680
or something like that, where you look down at the road and people look like ants.

491
00:28:44,680 --> 00:28:48,680
Well, that's because they look really small when you're far away.

492
00:28:48,680 --> 00:28:53,320
On the other hand, when you're up close, you realize, no, they're the normal size for people.

493
00:28:53,320 --> 00:28:56,520
And that sort of phenomenon is every day.

494
00:28:56,520 --> 00:29:01,360
So yes, the sizes of things can vary, not only from context to context.

495
00:29:01,360 --> 00:29:06,480
I mean, something might look much smaller if I put it next to something that's really large.

496
00:29:06,480 --> 00:29:10,960
And in fact, often people, to take a photograph of something really large, will put something

497
00:29:10,960 --> 00:29:14,760
next to it or have a person stand next to it or something so that you get a sense of

498
00:29:14,760 --> 00:29:19,040
scale and so that you can see, look, I know it looks small in the photograph, this thing

499
00:29:19,040 --> 00:29:21,240
is really large.

500
00:29:21,240 --> 00:29:26,800
And that's because all of these things can affect our perception, our perception of primary

501
00:29:26,800 --> 00:29:27,880
qualities.

502
00:29:27,880 --> 00:29:31,920
The same thing can happen with respect to something like mass or motion.

503
00:29:31,920 --> 00:29:37,760
The same motion might feel very fast or very slow, depending upon the context.

504
00:29:37,760 --> 00:29:42,240
In this case, not how close we are to it, though that can be true too, watch an airplane

505
00:29:42,240 --> 00:29:43,320
go across the sky.

506
00:29:43,320 --> 00:29:46,960
The plane is going at hundreds of miles an hour, but it looks for our vantage point

507
00:29:46,960 --> 00:29:50,200
on the ground as if it's traveling very slowly.

508
00:29:50,200 --> 00:29:53,200
The same thing can happen if you've ever flown a plane.

509
00:29:53,200 --> 00:29:54,520
I have.

510
00:29:54,520 --> 00:30:00,080
And when you stop flying a plane and get into your car, for example, the speed you're going

511
00:30:00,080 --> 00:30:03,720
in a car feels so unbelievably slow.

512
00:30:03,720 --> 00:30:08,920
I had a friend who was a pilot and he was constantly getting speeding tickets.

513
00:30:08,920 --> 00:30:12,240
And it's not really just because he was the kind of person who speeds a lot and ignores

514
00:30:12,240 --> 00:30:13,240
the law.

515
00:30:13,240 --> 00:30:18,520
It's because when you've been up in an airplane, the speeds you get used to are the speeds

516
00:30:18,520 --> 00:30:20,680
of going hundreds of miles an hour.

517
00:30:20,680 --> 00:30:26,120
When you then are on the ground traveling at 60, it feels like you're crawling.

518
00:30:26,120 --> 00:30:30,000
And so that kind of thing is a phenomenon we're familiar with.

519
00:30:30,000 --> 00:30:32,920
But wait, velocity was a primary quality.

520
00:30:32,920 --> 00:30:36,600
So is that airplane moving across the sky quickly or not?

521
00:30:36,600 --> 00:30:40,680
Well, we're perceiving a primary quality of motion there.

522
00:30:40,680 --> 00:30:45,840
But the feeling for the pilot and the feeling of us on the ground can't both be right.

523
00:30:45,840 --> 00:30:48,760
They can't both match the actual velocity.

524
00:30:48,760 --> 00:30:54,120
And the same thing is true of driving a car when you haven't driven in a while and then

525
00:30:54,120 --> 00:30:56,280
when you've been flying an airplane.

526
00:30:56,280 --> 00:31:00,560
It's the same velocity, but one time it feels fast to you, another time it feels slow.

527
00:31:00,560 --> 00:31:02,600
It can't be both fast and slow.

528
00:31:02,600 --> 00:31:06,380
But again, motion, velocity, is supposed to be a primary quality.

529
00:31:06,380 --> 00:31:10,120
So it looks like we're immediately led into trouble.

530
00:31:10,120 --> 00:31:14,080
Filonius concludes in the dialogue, this isn't in the object.

531
00:31:14,080 --> 00:31:18,720
He says, is it not the very same reasoning to conclude that there is no extension or

532
00:31:18,720 --> 00:31:20,520
a figure in an object?

533
00:31:20,520 --> 00:31:23,880
Because to one eye, it shall seem little, smooth, and round, while at the same time

534
00:31:23,880 --> 00:31:26,720
it appears to the other great, uneven, and regular.

535
00:31:26,720 --> 00:31:32,600
Hylis, who is defending the Lochte-Cart point of view in the dialogue, says, the very same.

536
00:31:32,600 --> 00:31:34,720
But does this latter fact ever happen?

537
00:31:34,720 --> 00:31:38,920
Filonius says you may at any time make the experiment by looking with one eye bare and

538
00:31:38,920 --> 00:31:41,000
with another through a microscope.

539
00:31:41,000 --> 00:31:47,640
So doubt the examples I've given about mites, about speeds of airplanes, about other things.

540
00:31:47,640 --> 00:31:52,200
Maybe they don't convince you, but Filo says, hey, look at a leaf.

541
00:31:52,200 --> 00:31:53,960
Here's how a leaf looks every day.

542
00:31:53,960 --> 00:31:58,960
And we can describe, not just its secondary qualities, its green and so on, but its primary

543
00:31:58,960 --> 00:32:07,520
qualities, describe its shape, describe the actual figure that it corresponds to, describe

544
00:32:07,520 --> 00:32:11,880
it in any way you like, and now look through a microscope.

545
00:32:11,880 --> 00:32:14,240
It looks like that.

546
00:32:15,240 --> 00:32:21,120
Now, yes, its secondary qualities have changed, but the primary qualities have changed too.

547
00:32:21,120 --> 00:32:24,640
That bottom edge, for example, looks smooth.

548
00:32:24,640 --> 00:32:26,000
It's not smooth.

549
00:32:26,000 --> 00:32:27,720
It's pretty bumpy.

550
00:32:27,720 --> 00:32:32,440
And the same thing is going to be true of all sorts of primary qualities of the thing.

551
00:32:32,440 --> 00:32:35,680
Your perception will be very different through a microscope.

552
00:32:35,680 --> 00:32:38,200
You'll be seeing it very up close.

553
00:32:38,200 --> 00:32:44,200
And your perception of the size, of the velocity, of the shape, all of that is going to

554
00:32:44,200 --> 00:32:45,840
be quite different.

555
00:32:45,840 --> 00:32:51,280
Conclusion, Barclay draws, there's no distinction between primary and secondary qualities.

556
00:32:51,280 --> 00:32:53,320
They're all in the mind alone.

557
00:32:53,320 --> 00:32:58,280
If we insist on using those terms at all, the point is all of those qualities are really

558
00:32:58,280 --> 00:33:00,240
secondary qualities.

559
00:33:00,240 --> 00:33:06,280
And so we should be idealists about all qualities, none of them are in the things themselves.

560
00:33:06,280 --> 00:33:09,160
They are all in the mind alone.

561
00:33:09,160 --> 00:33:12,720
Everything is really a construction or a projection of the mind.

562
00:33:12,760 --> 00:33:16,680
Every single quality we attribute to an object is mind dependent.

563
00:33:16,680 --> 00:33:17,680
It is variable.

564
00:33:17,680 --> 00:33:18,680
It is separable.

565
00:33:18,680 --> 00:33:25,800
It is the kind of thing that is there in the mind, but is not there in the object.

566
00:33:25,800 --> 00:33:29,320
I want to leave you with a question.

567
00:33:29,320 --> 00:33:33,920
We've been attacking here with Barclay that distinction between the primary and secondary

568
00:33:33,920 --> 00:33:35,520
qualities.

569
00:33:35,520 --> 00:33:37,840
But could we do this in a different way?

570
00:33:37,840 --> 00:33:42,680
Instead of saying all qualities are really primary, could we do it in the opposite way?

571
00:33:42,680 --> 00:33:44,600
Actually, they're all in the object.

572
00:33:44,600 --> 00:33:46,600
They're all primary qualities.

573
00:33:46,600 --> 00:33:52,360
Now notice we would have to get rid of Locke's idea that everything before the mind is really

574
00:33:52,360 --> 00:33:53,360
an idea.

575
00:33:53,360 --> 00:33:56,040
We'd have to say, no, I can perceive the triangle.

576
00:33:56,040 --> 00:33:59,240
I don't have to just have an idea before the mind.

577
00:33:59,240 --> 00:34:01,920
The triangle can really be before my mind.

578
00:34:01,920 --> 00:34:09,720
I would also have to say that actually these tests of constancy and invariableness, maybe

579
00:34:09,720 --> 00:34:11,400
those aren't the right tests.

580
00:34:11,400 --> 00:34:13,560
The right test is something else.

581
00:34:13,560 --> 00:34:18,000
But even a secondary quality, maybe I could push all of those into the thing.

582
00:34:18,000 --> 00:34:22,280
I can say, ah, you think the yellow isn't really in the paper?

583
00:34:22,280 --> 00:34:23,440
What if it is?

584
00:34:23,440 --> 00:34:28,080
What if we end up saying, look, being yellow is just reflecting certain wavelengths of

585
00:34:28,080 --> 00:34:29,080
light.

586
00:34:29,080 --> 00:34:31,400
And the paper really does reflect those wavelengths.

587
00:34:31,400 --> 00:34:34,680
That really is a quality of the paper itself.

588
00:34:34,680 --> 00:34:41,200
I think these arguments, as framed, are quite effective against the way Locke sets it all

589
00:34:41,200 --> 00:34:42,400
up.

590
00:34:42,400 --> 00:34:47,280
But maybe the general problem of mind and world here could be addressed in a kind of

591
00:34:47,280 --> 00:34:50,360
Barclayan spirit, but in a different way.

592
00:34:50,360 --> 00:34:55,600
Instead of pushing the world up into the mind, maybe we could push the mind in effect down

593
00:34:55,600 --> 00:35:03,000
into the world and say, actually all of those ideas are about things in the world.

594
00:35:03,000 --> 00:35:05,000
Our thinking is about the things.

595
00:35:05,000 --> 00:35:06,880
It's not about the ideas.

596
00:35:06,880 --> 00:35:09,080
The thing can itself be before the mind.

597
00:35:09,080 --> 00:35:13,320
We can make direct reference to the thing in our thoughts and in our language.

598
00:35:13,320 --> 00:35:18,480
And maybe we could instead then say, actually all those qualities are really in the things

599
00:35:18,480 --> 00:35:19,480
themselves.

600
00:35:19,480 --> 00:35:21,840
They're all primary qualities.

601
00:35:21,840 --> 00:35:25,000
It's not just a question of affecting us in certain ways.

602
00:35:25,000 --> 00:35:29,520
Being red might be reflecting wavelengths of light of a certain kind.

603
00:35:29,520 --> 00:35:31,160
Same thing with being yellow.

604
00:35:31,160 --> 00:35:34,840
Maybe the same thing is true of all of the other secondary qualities.

605
00:35:34,840 --> 00:35:40,280
So even if Barclay succeeds at denying the distinction, maybe we don't have to become

606
00:35:40,280 --> 00:35:42,680
idealists about everything.

607
00:35:42,680 --> 00:35:48,160
Could we instead become realists about all of it and attribute all of this to the things

608
00:35:48,160 --> 00:35:48,920
themselves?

